'''Antonis Antoniadis''' (born in [[1945]]) is one of the great goal scorers of the [[Greece|Greek]] [[soccer|football]] era after the "war" years, scoring about '''148 goals in 22 years of career'''. He started his career playing for [[Skoda Xanthi|Xanthi]] and then moved on to [[Panathinaikos]]. Antoniadis scored his first official goal with [[Panathinaikos]] on the [[October 27|27th of October]] [[1968]] in the game against [[Apollon Athens]] which ended in a victory for Panathinaikos with 1-0. 

He scored 187 goals in 242 matches of the [[Alpha Ethniki|Greek Championship]], and held the crown of first scorer five times: 1970 with 25 goals, 1972 with 39 goals (second in Europe), 1973 with 22 goals, 1974 with 26 goals, and 1975 with 20 goals. In [[European Cup 1970-71|1971]] when Panathinaikos reached the final in [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] for the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions Cup]] he was the top scorer of the tournament with 10 goals. 

Summer of [[1978]] he was traded to [[Olympiakos]] with whom he stayed for one season, playing in 13 games and scoring 7 goals. He later went on to play for [[Atromitos|Atromitos Athens]]. In 1980 before he retired and became president of PSAP he went full circle and returned to Panathinaikos. Very good using his head as well as he had a strong shot. He has 21 appearances and 6 goals with the [[Greece national football team|Greek national team]] in the period of 1970-1977.

